(35, '1667215043691x880514795796693000', '', '', '', 'No-Code or Low-Code: That is the Question', 'With all the mentioned advantages, here comes the question: what technologies should one select? What is the best option for a particular business?\nThere is no clear answer to this question. If you need a web app, a marketplace for designers’ projects or some kind of CRM, both no-code and low-code tools are perfect to implement these ideas. Still, it’s necessary to analyze the complexity of the project. \n\nClosed vs Open System\n\nWith no-code instruments, you can be a bit limited in your abilities and creativity. Any no-code platform is a kind of closed system. You benefit from a certain set of templates and plugins available within this system. However, you can create quite functional and powerful products. For instance, the Bubble platform allows enriching the products with a variety of custom elements let alone API integrations.  \n\nOne of the advantages of low-code technologies is that they give you even more freedom. Low-code platforms are the so-called ‘open’ system. Developers can change the code whenever necessary at any step of product development. Moreover, these tools boast extensive component libraries. One can create more sophisticated products.\n\nAn excellent example of low-code instruments in action is a student-tutor communication platform. With the help of this platform, one can easily schedule classes and communicate with teachers. Our developers used the Bubble platform, as well as integrated Google Forms and Google Sheets. Besides this, they take advantage of custom code to create a virtual whiteboard. The iFrame made it possible to add video chat Jitsi between teacher and student. This HTML element allows embedding documents, videos, interactive media files, and other pieces of content from different sources on a web page.\n\nAs you can see, low-code technologies are more flexible and, as a result, more powerful.\nThus, both no-code and low-co